Etymology. Nothing is known about the life history of these beetles, as they have been rarely collected alive. Most of the few specimens that have been found were dead on the ground, and it is possible that the adults are found in dead wood that is infrequently collected and high off the ground (
Paulsen 2005
). The name is derived from the Greek caeno (recent) and olethros (death), to approximate ‘recently deceased,’ as most specimens are when encountered. The gender is masculine.
